{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"29fc881e-06d0-4b09-954b-455a78baabc1","content":"Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` file in your workspace root with this configuration:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- If your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` field.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the executable.\n\nAfter saving, open the **Command Palette** → **MCP: List Servers** to verify VS Code detects it, then start it from there or let agent mode auto-start it when a relevant tool is invoked.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9dbc7aec-b4ba-4732-af0d-380f1ee23f46","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist, but that's fine — the user is asking how to configure `mcp.json`, not asking me to build the project. I can provide guidance on the configuration.\n\nFor VS Code agent mode, you configure MCP servers in `.vscode/mcp.json` at the workspace root. For a C# MCP server using stdio transport, you'd use `dotnet run` as the command.","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"B01A:100751:D762CE:F4123C:6A027D6C"},"id":"c02787e3-6871-470d-b2ef-a390630b23d2","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:08:06.260Z","parentId":"e8b15648-48fd-4f33-82df-a8f1feb0402c"}
